🧭 1. Why Sanskrit is called “eternal”

Short answer:
👉 Not because it literally fell from the sky
👉 But because it behaves like a perfectly stabilized system

The traditional claim

In Hindu traditions:
	•	Sanskrit is not invented, but revealed (śruti)
	•	Sound itself (śabda) is considered fundamental to reality
	•	The Vedas are “heard,” not written

⸻

The structural reason (the real engine)

Sanskrit is insanely formalized, especially through
Pāṇini

He created one of the most precise grammar systems ever:
	•	~4,000 rules
	•	Generative (like code)
	•	Minimal + complete

It’s basically:

language = rule system that can generate all valid expressions

👉 This makes it feel:
	•	timeless
	•	closed
	•	complete

⸻

Why that feels “eternal”

Because:

If a system doesn’t drift → it feels outside time

Sanskrit (especially Classical Sanskrit) was:
	•	tightly preserved
	•	rarely allowed to mutate casually
	•	transmitted with precision

So it feels like:

“This didn’t evolve… it exists”

